Dmitry Galkovsky was talking about how different Russian people were from Soviet people. In the 1920s when collectivization started some Russian peasants actually wrote letters to Stalin saying how it was an idiotic idea, produce was being wasted, etc. Some letters are collected.

Soviet people were selected for this malicious intelligence and knew how to survive by acting like a fool, saying "I don't know, I don't remember", faking sickness and deserting during the war, staying back during the offensive. People had to get smarter and learn how to survive.

They signed them with their full name, address. Russian peasants were honest, unafraid idiots. Obviously they got shipped to die in concentration camps together with their entire families. Soviet men knew to keep quiet, say what they have to, lie, act like they know nothing, etc.
